HRVs have been subclassified using tissue tropism and host range, antiviral susceptibility and phylogeny. Early sequencing of subgenomic RT-PCR amplicons also identified the presence of two viral clades, subsequently defined as the HRV species (Mori and Clewley, 1994), a distinctive bifurcation retained when sequences from other subgenomic regions, including P1, 2C and 3CD (Fig. 1
) are compared. Today, sequencing and phylogenetic comparison is a surrogate for all the important biological classification criteria (Savolainen et al., 2002, Savolainen et al., 2004, Ledford et al., 2004, Laine et al., 2005, Laine et al., 2006, King et al., 2000, Hungnes et al., 2000) (Table 1
).
